<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="965" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d965">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/15959</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to President <persName type="to">Roosevelt</persName></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-13">June 13, 1940</date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Before your memorandum of June 13 in regard to the apparently
                                indiscriminate bombing of Chungking was brought to my attention, I
                                issued to the press a statement on this subject,<note n="71" xml:id="d965fn71"><ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_690"><hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941,
                                        Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 690</ref>.</note> a
                                copy of which is enclosed for convenience of reference. In the light
                                of your memorandum, I am also telegraphing Ambassador Grew at
                                    Tokyo<note n="72" xml:id="d965fn72">Telegram No. 197, June 13, 5
                                    p.m., not printed.</note> to bring that statement to the
                                personal attention of the Japanese Minister for Foreign Affairs.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cordell Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>